After the Liberal International Order
Cambridge—Many analysts believe that the liberal international order ended with the rise of China and the election of U.S. President Donald Trump.
But if Joe Biden defeats Trump in the November election, should he try to revive it?
Perhaps not, but he must find some alternative.
Critics are right to point out that the American order after 1945 was neither truly global nor always very liberal.
It excludes more than half of the world (including the Soviet bloc and China) and includes many authoritarian countries.
American hegemony is always exaggerated.
Nevertheless, the most powerful countries must lead in creating global public goods, otherwise they will not be provided — and Americans will also suffer as a result.
The current pandemic is a good example of this.
A realistic goal of the Biden administration should be to establish an international system based on rules, with different member states participating in handling different issues.
Would China and Russia be willing to participate?
In the 1990s and the 21st century, both countries were unable to balance American power, while the United States, transcending sovereignty, remained committed to the pursuit of liberal values.
The United States bombed Serbia and invaded Iraq without the approval of the United Nations Security Council.
It also supported a "Responsibility to Protect" resolution passed by the United Nations General Assembly in 2005, aimed at protecting citizens from their own governments' brutal treatment — later, in 2011, the United States used this principle to justify bombing Libya to protect citizens of Benghazi.
Critics describe this record as the arrogance of Americans in the post-Cold War era — for example, when the NATO-led intervention in Libya ultimately led to a regime change, Russia and China felt deceived — while defenders of this action describe it as the natural evolution of international humanitarian law.
No matter what, the growth of China's and Russia's power more strictly limits the actions of liberal interventionism.
So what remains?
Russia and China emphasize the principle of sovereignty stipulated in the UN Charter, which stipulates that states can only wage war for self-defense or with the approval of the Security Council.
Since 1945, the occupation of neighboring countries' territories by force has been very rare, and when it does happen, it incurs a high cost due to sanctions (such as Russia's annexation of Crimea in 2014).
Furthermore, the Security Council frequently authorizes the deployment of peacekeeping forces in countries in distress, and political cooperation has also successfully limited the expansion of weapons of mass destruction and ballistic missiles.
The rule-based dimension of order remains crucial.
Specifically regarding economic relations, the world needs to revise the rules.
Even before the pandemic, China's hybrid state capitalism supported an unfair mercantilist model, which distorted the functions of the WTO.
The result will lead to the decoupling of global supply chains, especially when national security is under threat.
Although China complains that the US is blocking companies like Huawei from building 5G communication networks in the West, the US position is consistent with sovereignty claims.
After all, China has blocked the operations of Google, Facebook, and Twitter within its borders for security reasons.
Negotiating new trade rules will help prevent the escalation of decoupling.
Meanwhile, despite the current crisis, cooperation in key financial areas remains very strong.
On the contrary, mutual dependence in the ecological field creates insurmountable obstacles in the face of sovereignty, as the threats are transboundary.
No matter how much economic globalization is hindered, environmental globalization will continue, as it follows biological and physical laws, which are unaffected by contemporary geopolitical logic.
The above issues threaten everyone, but no country is capable of solving them independently.
In issues such as the 2019 COVID-19 pandemic and climate change, power also has so-called positive-sum dimensions.
Under such premises, merely thinking about exercising power over others is insufficient.
We must also contemplate the dimension of exercising power jointly with other countries.
The Paris Climate Agreement and the World Health Organization are helpful to us and to others.
Since Nixon and Mao met in 1972, despite ideological differences, this has not affected cooperation between China and the United States.
The challenge Biden faces is whether the United States and China can cooperate in producing global public goods while competing in traditional areas of great power rivalry.
Cyberspace is a new and important issue — because it has a transnational character to some extent, but is also controlled by sovereign governments.
The internet has already been partially fragmented.
Rules for internet freedom of speech and privacy can be established within democratic countries, but these rules will not be recognized by authoritarian countries.
As suggested by the Global Commission on the Stability of Cyberspace, if authoritarian regimes also wish to achieve interconnectivity, certain rules that prohibit tampering with the fundamental structure of the internet would also be in their interests.
However, when they use proxies to conduct information warfare or interfere in elections (practices that infringe upon sovereignty), norms must be reinforced through rules such as those negotiated during the Cold War between the United States and the Soviet Union to limit escalation of maritime incidents (although hostility in the ideological sphere remains).
The United States and like-minded countries must publicly state the norms they intend to uphold and establish the necessary deterrents.
Adhering to the values of freedom in cyberspace does not mean the United States unilaterally disarms.
On the contrary, the United States should distinguish between permissible soft power such as open persuasion and hard power such as covert information warfare, and certainly retaliate when the other side launches covert information warfare.
It is permissible for Russia and China to openly broadcast programs and radio, but secret unifying actions such as manipulating social media are not allowed.
Moreover, the US will continue to criticize the human rights records of these countries.
Public opinion surveys show that the American public wants to avoid military intervention but does not want to exit alliances or multilateral cooperation.
Moreover, the public still values its values.
If Biden is elected, the issue he faces is not whether to restore the liberal international order.
The issue is whether the United States can work with its core allies to promote democracy and human rights, while simultaneously collaborating with a broader range of countries to manage transnational threats such as climate change, pandemics, cyber attacks, terrorism, and economic instability through rules-based international institutions.
